{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659526","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659526"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:09:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:09:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20865"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20865","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20865"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.17,0.58,0,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13740"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96498"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13740"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20865"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79140"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11595"},{"type":"tags","id":"12319"},{"type":"tags","id":"12687"},{"type":"tags","id":"12688"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33068"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33069"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96498","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96498"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman is diagnosed with Sj\u00f6gren syndrome after presenting with a two-year history of dry eyes, dry mouth, and difficulty swallowing dry foods. She also reports recurrent oral ulcers and dental caries despite good oral hygiene. Examination reveals dry, erythematous conjunctivae and a dry, fissured tongue.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the histopathological findings in the salivary glands of this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Squamous metaplasia of ductal epithelium","Amyloid deposition in glandular tissue","Periductal and perivascular lymphocytic infiltration","Neutrophilic abscesses within glandular tissue","Granulomatous inflammation with caseation necrosis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has Sj\u00f6gren syndrome, an autoimmune disorder characterized by dry eyes (keratoconjunctivitis sicca) and dry mouth (xerostomia). The histopathological hallmark of Sj\u00f6gren syndrome is \u003Cstrong\u003Eperiductal and perivascular lymphocytic infiltration\u003C/strong\u003E of the affected exocrine glands. This lymphocytic infiltration is the earliest histologic finding in the salivary glands.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs the disease progresses, the lymphocytic infiltrate becomes more extensive, and lymphoid follicles with germinal centers may develop. Later stages show ductal epithelial hyperplasia, acinar atrophy, fibrosis, and hyalinization. Eventually, there is replacement of the parenchyma with fat.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESquamous metaplasia of ductal epithelium\u003C/strong\u003E - While ductal epithelial changes occur in Sj\u00f6gren syndrome, they typically manifest as hyperplasia rather than squamous metaplasia.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmyloid deposition in glandular tissue\u003C/strong\u003E - This can be seen in amyloidosis but is not a feature of Sj\u00f6gren syndrome.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeutrophilic abscesses within glandular tissue\u003C/strong\u003E - This would suggest an acute bacterial infection rather than the chronic autoimmune inflammation seen in Sj\u00f6gren syndrome.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGranulomatous inflammation with caseation necrosis\u003C/strong\u003E - This is characteristic of tuberculosis and other mycobacterial infections, not Sj\u00f6gren syndrome.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that the intense lymphocytic infiltration in Sj\u00f6gren syndrome can sometimes resemble lymphoma, and these patients have an increased risk of developing B-cell lymphomas.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Sj\u00f6gren syndrome primarily affects lacrimal and salivary glands, causing dry eyes and dry mouth.","The histopathology of Sj\u00f6gren syndrome shows lymphocytic infiltration of exocrine glands, with eventual acinar atrophy and fibrosis.","Patients with Sj\u00f6gren syndrome have an increased risk of developing B-cell lymphomas."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 6; pages 229-231."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79140"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20865"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79140","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79140"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-01T17:52:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-01T17:54:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13740"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96498"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11595"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diseases of the immune system","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":5,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T20:55:18+10:30","